natural problem: What is the greatest integer that satisfies $6 - x > -9$ ?
natural solution: Adding $x+9$ to both sides gives $$6-x+x+9 > -9+x+9,$$ then simplifying gives $$15 > x.$$ The greatest integer satisfying this inequality is $x=\boxed{14}$.

theorem
fixes x :: int
assumes h0 : "6 - x > -9"
shows  "GREATEST x. x = 14"
